related_questions.question: How do I find my IP address?
related_questions.title: AI Overview
list: 1.  Using a website: Go to WhatIsMyIP.org or WhatIsMyIPAddress.com. The website will display your public IP address.
2.  Using a search engine: Search "what is my IP address" on Google. The search result will display your public IP address.
Open the Command Prompt by pressing the Windows key, typing "cmd", and pressing Enter.
Your IP address will be listed under "IPv4 Address".
Open Terminal by going to Applications > Utilities > Terminal.
Your IP address will be listed under the "en0" (Wi-Fi) or "en1" (Ethernet) section.

related_questions.question: Is 192.168 my IP address?
related_questions.title: AI Overview
list: Local IP Addresses: . Opens in new tab192.168.x.x (where x can be any number from 0 to 255) is a common range for private IP addresses.
Router's Role: . Opens in new tabYour modem/router assigns these private IP addresses to devices within your home network (computers, phones, smart TVs, etc.).

Public IP Address: . Opens in new tabYour public IP address is what the rest of the internet sees when you connect. It's how websites and other online services know where to send information back to your network.

NAT: . Opens in new tabYour router uses Network Address Translation (NAT) to translate between the private IP addresses on your local network and your single public IP address when communicating with the internet, according to Avast.

related_questions.question: How do I find my public IP address?
related_questions.title: AI Overview
list: 1.  Open a web browser: . Opens in new tabLaunch your preferred web browser, such as Chrome, Firefox, or Safari.
2.  Go to a website that detects IP addresses: . Opens in new tabType whatismyipaddress.com or whatismyip.com into the address bar and press Enter.
3.  Alternatively, use a search engine: . Opens in new tabOpen a search engine (like Google) and type "what is my IP address" into the search bar.
4.  View your public IP address: . Opens in new tabThe website will display your public IPv4 or IPv6 address, which is the address other devices use to communicate with you over the internet.
